Introduction

The alarming, global increase of air pollution and temperature is a matter that people simply cannot ignore anymore. It is directly affecting people’s health, even to the extremity of death according to doctors, epidemilogotists, and reports of death rates in higher levels of air pollution. (1) It is significant to analyze these levels of air pollution and temperature and their relationship with mortality to figure out what exact factors could improve health and lifespans. First, we need to see if there is evidence that these pollutants are associated with increased mortality, and which exact pollutant has the strongest association with mortality. In addition, we would like to see if the effect of pollution is instantaneous or if it extends over time. Lastly, we would like to what would be the estimated mean death ratefor a 70-degree day if the level of each pollutant were lowered to the lowest value ever recorded. Having the answers to all of our research objectives and questions would lead us to the conclusion of whether Preston Jorgensen should spend his fortune to try to reduce pollution that much. (2) For in-depth and simplicity reasons, we will focus on the air quality in Chicago, Illinois from January 1987 to the end of December 2000. The corresponding dataset will contain 5,114 observations of 6 variables: time (date of observation), death (number of non-accidental deaths on that date), pm10median (median density of \(PM_{10}\) pollution), o3median (median concentration of ozone, parts per billion), so2median (median concentration of sulfur dioxide), and tmpd (mean temperature, Farenheit). However, due to many NA values, we will remove these observations since it would affect our results. Throughout this report, we will be working on our Chicago datset that has 4012 nonempty observations of 6 variables. In addition, there are two versions: median data and 7-day lagged data. (3) Overall the final findings of this report will include the discussion of how much air pollutants affect human’s health by observing their death rates. We will also look into how mortality would change when altering air pollutants values, and how it does decrease the number of mortality. And finally, we will see how the 7-day average of medium concentrations of air pollutants are actually better variables to look into due to their strong association with mortality when analyzing our research objectives.

Sulfur dioxide and particulate matter both are highly skewed to the right where their peak is near 0. Ozone is also skewed to the right but not as drastically. Temperature is skewed to the left with two peaks.

Next let’s look into the lagged versions of our key variables. Both lagged and unlagged versions have the same skewness patterns, and their peaks’ locations seem to be similar too. However, the lagged version also does seem to be more wide than the unlagged version.

Thus, we could possibly expect to see temperature to be our biggest indicator of mortality rate out of all of the air pollutants.

Modeling & Diagnostics

(1) Now let’s make models to see how they fit with our data. We’ll do this by fitting 2 Poisson generalized additive models to the data, one with unlagged versions of our air pollutants and other with lagged versions of our air pollutants. For simplicity of better fitting and speed reasons, we will use spline smoother terms for all variables and use 4 degrees of freedom. That way, we could potentially observe the models better.

(2) Let’s further analyze the models to determine which model fits best for our chicago data. We could do this by using 5-fold cross-validation to make comparisons on their prediction errors. After running our unlagged and lagged model data through our function, our average mean squared error for unlagged is 200.9835 with the standard error of 22.24936, and our average mean squared error for lagged is 186.9713 with the standard error of 20.24234. (3) The difference in the cross-validation errors between our two models is 14.3122. This value does not appear significant based on the uncertainy in our estimates, however this is not based on a statistical test. However, based on our prediction errors from our 5-fold cross-validation, our lagged model performed better than our unlagged model in MSE and standard error. Thus, we will use our lagged model for our results.

Results

(1) Like we mentioned before, our lagged model has the best performance due to its low prediction error. Let’s confirm this further by conducting a global goodness-of-fit of this model with a chi-squared test. Our p-value indicates that there is no evidence to reject our lagged model. Based on these results, we can claim that our model actually fits our dataset well. (2) To determine whether the pollutants are associated with mortality, we fit a model that only uses temperature as a feature, not the pollutants. Then we ran an anova test on this model along with our lagged model. Based on the anova test, we can see that the p-value is extremely low and the deviance of our new model is 236.59. This implies that our lagged model significantly improves on Model 3 and once again proves to be a better model. This also supports the claim that air pollutants do have some effect on mortality.(3) Overall, the effect of pollution appears to extend over time. This is due to our cross-validation results that showed that our lagged model has a lower prediction error than our unlagged model.

(4) Let’s now visualize our model to have a better insight of their associations. Figure 4 displays our lagged additive model’s average relationship between each key variable and the outcome. We can observe its standard error bands and how death rates change as the 7-days average median concentration air pollutants increase. The plot with sulfur oxide shows to decrease after its peak around 0 and increases slowly again after 5 parts per billion, and the plot with particulate matter increases slow until around 38 and gently plateaus. The plot with temperature shows a decreasing association. However, the plot with ozone shows a sharp increase after 10 parts per billion of ozone medium concentration. Thus, based on these plots, mortality seems to be the most affected by ozone.

Lagged Additive Model Plots with Uncertainty

(5) Next, let’s calculate the smallest value observed for each pollution variable with our chosen model for the mean number of deaths on a 70-degree day with those level of pollutans. This would allow us to understand the impact of the lagged variables onto the model. By creating a new data frame with all the values setted to the wanted conditions, the 95% confidence interval turned out to be [106.3424, 114.5066].

(6) Next we will conduct 1000 bootstrap iterations to uncover the pivotal confidence interval for average number of deaths. Non-parametric bootstrapping with resampling would be the most appropriate choice so that we don’t have to worry about assumptions such as normality and constant variance. The 95% confidence interval from our 1000 bootstrap iterations is [114.4845, 114.9651]. (7) Our bootstrapped confidence interval’s range is much smaller than the confidence interval calculated for the model of smallest values. Like we mentioned before, non-parametric bootstrapping method overlooks few assumptions. Thus, their confidence interval is much smaller.

Conclusions

(1) Overall, there is indeed a significant association between atmospheric pollutants and mortality. From our new model that only considered the temperature variable, we saw that our lagged model improved much upon it, proving to be significant. In addition, our 5-fold cross-validation and additive model plots also proved that air pollutants do affect mortality but also its effect extend over time. (2) As our client Preston Jorgensen requested, we have gathered results and evidence that reducing pollutants would cause mortality to decrease. When we created a new model that setted all the air pollutants to its minimum, there was a clear decrease in the number of deaths. However, it is difficult to claim that this officially as a conclusion. Observing our dataset, there are some observations with fewer deaths, so this claim is not confidently official. Though this was a thorough analysis, there are a few limitations that could need discussion.(3) First, almost 20% of the orignal dataset was removed due to containing NA observations. This was beneficial to our analysis to conduct meaningful conclusions and test. However, this is definitely a limitation since it is still a big chunk of data that we ignored. In addition, only analyzing observations from one city is another limitation. It is incorrect to generalize the effects of air pollutants on mortality, but it would be definitely be more interesting to sample more observations from other parts around the world.
